{
  "slug": "ad-astra-is-a-masterpiece-and-brad-pitt-has-won-2019-plus-ja",
  "title": "'Ad Astra' Is a Masterpiece, and Brad Pitt Has Won 2019. Plus: James Gray on Making His Space Epic.",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2019-09-20",
  "runtimeMin": 116,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda argue Brad Pitt is winning 2019, rank their favorite Pitt performances, and Sean talks to 'Ad Astra' director James Gray.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Ad Astra'",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Ad Astra",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Pitt is Roy McBride, an astronaut sent to find his father (Tommy Lee Jones), who left on a mission to a far-off planet. A quiet, meditative character study with three or four whiz-bang set pieces; Amanda was moved, both hosts flag that the marketing sets up a bigger space movie than the one Gray made."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "The Top Five Brad Pitt Performances",
      "note": "two hosts, two lists",
      "subject": "Brad Pitt",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Moneyball",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "Both hosts' No. 1. Billy Beane as the summation of every Brad Pitt mode (reserved, charming, dickhead-mean), carried on physical presence in nearly every frame."
        },
        {
          "title": "Inglourious Basterds",
          "year": 2009,
          "note": "Both hosts' No. 2. Sean floats the case that Pitt is 'bad' in it; the Aldo Raine cadence is a self-conscious, instantly quotable voice creation."
        },
        {
          "title": "Once Upon a Time in Hollywood",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Amanda's No. 4 (tied for 2). Cliff Booth as the perfect 2019 match of actor and character: Tarantino plucking a star to comment on his own fame."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "Amanda's No. 3. A historic bomb, now a cinephile favorite; Pitt plays James as a crotchety, ill-fitting icon. A triple feature with 'Ad Astra' and 'Once Upon a Time' on self-mythology and fathers."
        },
        {
          "title": "Burn After Reading",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "Amanda's No. 5. Chad Feldheimer, Pitt's funniest, most in-on-the-joke comedic performance, handsome with terrible hair."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ocean's Eleven",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Sean's No. 3. Peak cool-guy Pitt; the 'you think we need one more' bit is him doing nothing on a bar and being hilarious. Starts the Brad-Pitt-always-eating gimmick."
        },
        {
          "title": "Snatch",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "Sean's No. 4. A bare-knuckle-boxing British gypsy you can barely understand, probably the most physically imposing he's been on screen."
        },
        {
          "title": "Se7en",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "Sean's No. 5. Where a lot of guys met Pitt for real, and where David Fincher's sensibility first showed; the 'what's in the box' meltdown."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "James Gray on 'Ad Astra'",
      "guest": "James Gray on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Ad Astra",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Harder to make than his Amazon shoot: one-man scenes with no scene partner, zero-gravity wire work, all-CG backgrounds built from the ground up. About 90% of what he wanted; he cites plausibility over accuracy, and Brad Pitt bringing more than what was in his head."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Lost City of Z",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Pitt produced it via Plan B; Gray tried to put his feelings about fatherhood and family into it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Yards",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "Gray rewatched it and marveled at the cast (Wahlberg, Phoenix, Theron, Charlize), who weren't yet stars when he made it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Little Odessa",
          "year": 1994,
          "note": "His first film, made at 23; he says he'd never let himself make a movie that young now."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Immigrant",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "Cited as a film with more distance than 'Ad Astra': less subjective, less access to his interior life."
        },
        {
          "title": "We Own the Night",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "The provisional-officer plot people called bogus though it's real: Gray's example that believability on screen differs from real life."
        },
        {
          "title": "Two Lovers",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "He and Phoenix thought they were making a comedy, laughing on set; the first screening called it one of the saddest movies they'd seen."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
